<subSubSection id="C3106CCBFFAF7B0EFF122C48FCB346A8" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB53F40FFAF7B0EFF122C48FCB346A8" blockId="11.[192,1440,1597,1685]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFAF7B0EFF122C48FE8D4668" bold="true" box="[192,347,1597,1621]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named to recognize Edward G. Riley (TAMU), entomology researcher and author, who has been the collector of several new cerambycid species from 
<collectingCountry id="F31D7FD0FFAF7B0EFC432C2BFC2C4648" box="[913,1018,1630,1653]" name="Panama" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Panama</collectingCountry>
, including this one. Latin “-ellus”, used to form a diminutive of a noun. Masculine gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106CCBFFAF7B09FF122CD8FC824172" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB53F40FFAF7B09FF122CD8FC824172" blockId="11.[192,1441,1709,1926]" lastBlockId="12.[192,1440,215,335]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFAF7B0EFF122CD8FEB346F8" bold="true" box="[192,357,1709,1733]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Description.</emphasis>
Head not retractile, not prolonged behind eyes; frons transverse; antennal tubercles slightly elevated, distant from each other. Eyes not divided, coarsely faceted; distance between upper eye lobes larger than twice length of one lobe; lower eye lobes longer than gena. Antennae 11-segmented, distinctly longer than body; scape somewhat sinuous, gradually widened from base to about posterior quarter, then narrowed, lacking apical cicatrix, reaching about middle of prothoracic length; antennomeres filiform; antennomere III sinuous. Prothorax transverse; sides with large, conical tubercle. Pronotum with transverse crest about center. Procoxal cavities open laterally and posteriorly. Mesoventral process lacking tubercle. Mesocoxal cavities open laterally. Elytra with tuberculate centrobasal crest, lacking longitudinal carina, and with oblique/arched crests; outer apical angle rounded; with long, erect setae. Femora slightly pedunculate-clavate. Ventral surface of protibiae excavated on base of posterior third. Metatarsomere I slightly shorter than II–III together.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3106CCBFFA87B09FF122B1DFC98425D" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB53F40FFA87B09FF122B1DFC98425D" blockId="12.[191,1441,359,609]" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FF122B1DFE9541BD" bold="true" box="[192,323,360,384]" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FE9B2B12FE174142" authority="Wappes &amp; Santos-Silva, 2020" authorityName="Wappes &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2020" box="[329,449,359,383]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Rileyellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FE9B2B12FE174142" box="[329,449,359,383]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Rileyellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FE152B1DFD8E41BD" bold="true" box="[455,600,360,384]" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24D5E29FFA87B09FE152B1DFD8E41BD" box="[455,600,360,384]" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" rank="genus">new genus</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FD272B1DFB174142" authority="Galileo and Martins, 2006" authorityName="Galileo and Martins" authorityYear="2006" box="[757,1217,359,383]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Monnetyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FD272B1DFCAF4142" box="[757,889,360,383]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Monnetyra</emphasis>
Galileo and Martins, 2006
</taxonomicName>
, in the presence of a crest on the pronotum and elytra. However, it cannot be included in this genus because the prothorax has large lateral tubercles, which are absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FCD52BDCFC5D41FD" authorityName="Galileo and Martins" authorityYear="2006" box="[775,907,425,448]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Monnetyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FCD52BDCFC5D41FD" box="[775,907,425,448]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Monnetyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the mesotrochanters are not projected as a spine at apex (projected in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FD9C2BBCFD0741DD" authorityName="Galileo and Martins" authorityYear="2006" box="[590,721,457,480]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Monnetyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FD9C2BBCFD0741DD" box="[590,721,457,480]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Monnetyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The general appearance is also similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FA9D2BBDFEAA423D" authority="Thomson, 1864" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FA9D2BBDFA7741DD" box="[1359,1441,456,480]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Blabia</emphasis>
Thomson, 1864
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by the presence of a distinct transverse crest on pronotum (absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FA972B9DFA41423D" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[1349,1431,488,512]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FA972B9DFA41423D" box="[1349,1431,488,512]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Blabia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by the outer apical angle of the elytra being rounded (often spinose in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FB9F287DFB49421D" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[1101,1183,520,544]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FB9F287DFB49421D" box="[1101,1183,520,544]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Blabia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but never rounded). Additionally, the scape in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FDD9285DFD8B427D" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[523,605,552,576]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FDD9285DFD8B427D" box="[523,605,552,576]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Blabia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is typically not somewhat sinuous (except in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0A44C3FFA87B09FB48285CFEA4425C" authority="Galileo and Martins, 1998" authorityName="Galileo and Martins" authorityYear="1998" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banga">
<emphasis id="B97EE352FFA87B09FB48285CFADC427D" box="[1178,1290,552,576]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">B. banga</emphasis>
Galileo and Martins, 1998
</taxonomicName>
, which is likely generically misplaced).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
